Iteration 12: Proposed new text for instruction: You are given a piece of text (typically a question or phrase), and your task is to assign it to one of six categories: abbreviation, description, entity, human, location, or numeric. Your classification must precisely match the expected type of answer the text requests. Use the following detailed definitions and decision rules to guide your choices:

CATEGORIES & DECISION GUIDELINES:

1. abbreviation: Select this if the question is directly asking for the expansion, meaning, or explanation of an abbreviation, acronym, or initialism. Examples: “What does NATO stand for?”, “Expand the term CPU.” If the expected answer is the full phrase behind a set of initials, use abbreviation.

2. description: Choose this if the question is looking for a definition, explanation, process, summary, list, or other general descriptive information. Typical indicators include “describe,” “explain,” “what is/are” (if expecting a definition or explanation rather than a name), requests for lists of types, or procedures. CAUTION: If the answer is the name of a thing (not its explanation), DO NOT use description—use entity instead. If the answer is a fact or definition focusing on “what it is,” it’s likely description.

3. entity: Use this when the question is asking for the NAME or title of a SPECIFIC thing, concept, object, organization, event, work, animal, product, or species—anything concrete or categorical that is NOT a human or location. Indicators: “What/which is [the name of a thing]?,” “What do you call…?,” “Name a/an….” If the answer is a specific thing, species, object, or group (not a person or place, and not a process or definition), it’s an entity. For questions about most/least/biggest/best when expecting a thing or group name, use entity. Examples: “Which animal has the longest lifespan?”; “What color of Monopoly properties are landed on most often?”; “What is the chemical symbol for oxygen?”

4. human: Use this when the question is requesting the name or identity of a person, group of people, profession, historical figure, fictional character, team, or the role/title held by a person. Cues: “Who…,” “Which person…,” “Name a scientist who…,” or anything where the answer is a specific individual, group, or role. If the question is about a group primarily defined as humans, use human. Be careful: if the answer is an institution/organization (like a university), only use human if specifically asking for a group of people (e.g., “Who are the Harvard Crimson?”), not its name (entity).

5. location: Select this if the question is expecting a place: geographic area, city, country, address, building, body of water, mountain, site, region, or any spatial/geographical answer. Cues: “Where…,” “In what country/city…,” “Which mountain…?” Do NOT use entity for named locations—always use location if the answer is a place.

6. numeric: Use this if the answer should be a number, quantity, measurement, age, date, year, period, duration, or anything fundamentally numerical. Cues: “How many/much…,” “When…,” “What is the population/size/weight…?” For questions like “In what year was…,” choose numeric, not entity or description.

IMPORTANT FINE POINTS, BASED ON COMMON ERRORS:

- If the answer is the name of a thing (including types, categories, objects, colors, properties), choose entity, NOT description. For example, “What color of Monopoly properties are landed on most often?” expects a color name (entity). “Which gender has bigger thighs?” expects a gender (entity), not an explanation, so label as entity.

- Even when a question starts with “What is…,” consider if the answer is a name/thing (entity) or a dictionary-style explanation (description):  
  • “What is a wop?” (definition of a word) → description  
  • “What is the capital of France?” (expects city name) → location  
  • “What is titanium?” (if expecting a chemical element’s explanation/definition) → description; if asking for a symbol, name of a category, or type, then entity.

- For professions, groups of people, or collective humans, use human. For objects, organizations, products, animals, or defined things, use entity.  
  • “Which gender…?” expects gender name (entity)  
  • “Who discovered penicillin?” expects name of a human  
  • “Name the university of which Woodrow Wilson was president.” expects the name of an institution (entity), unless explicitly asking what group of people (faculty, etc.)

- For organizations or institutions, use entity unless the focus is on the people forming them (human). For universities, companies, or teams, ask whether the question expects an organization’s name (entity) or a group (human).

- For ambiguous or edge cases, always ask: “What is the expected answer’s *form*?” If in doubt between description and entity, if the answer is a *name/thing/category*, choose entity.

- Don’t confuse a request for a type of thing with a description—if the answer takes the form of a categorical or concrete label (color, species, gender, type), use entity.

YOUR OUTPUT FORMAT:
Return ONLY the label (abbreviation, description, entity, human, location, numeric).
Do not include explanations, justifications, or any other text.

EXAMPLES:
Text: “Who discovered penicillin?” → human  
Text: “What is the capital of France?” → location  
Text: “When was the Declaration of Independence signed?” → numeric  
Text: “What is the chemical formula for water?” → entity  
Text: “What does NASA stand for?” → abbreviation  
Text: “Explain the process of photosynthesis.” → description  
Text: “What color of Monopoly properties are landed on most often?” → entity  
Text: “Which gender has bigger thighs?” → entity  
Text: “What London museum features a Chamber of Horrors?” → location  

